AB  - The stigma accompanying major depressive disorder (MDD) increases distress and misery worldwide and may incur worse consequences than the condition itself. Over the last decades public knowledge about mental illnesses has increased, but public mental illness stigma has not decreased. Recent research suggests that endorsement of the continuum perspective on mental illness, particularly depression, has the potential to reduce stigma. We examined the impact of the continuum perspective on mental illness stigma (social distance, negative stereotypes) regarding MDD, hypothesizing that an increased endorsement of the continuum perspective would be associated with lower levels of stigma. Participants, recruited through Amazon's Mechanical Turk, included 487 adults, randomly assigned to one of two conditions containing different information about the nature of depression (continuum vs. categorical perspective) or to a control condition with neutral information. After reading a vignette about someone suffering from depression, participants completed a continuum-beliefs measure and stigma-related questionnaires. Sociodemographic variables, along with the variable of positive former contact with someone experiencing mental illness, were measured. The intervention did not reduce stigma toward individuals with depression. Higher mental health continuum beliefs were related to lower stigma against people with MDD across groups. Moreover, people assigned to the continuum intervention had significantly higher continuum beliefs; positive former contact was positively related to both continuum beliefs and lowered stigma. While findings suggest continuum beliefs and stigma are correlated, we discuss reasons why interventions seem to not (or only partially) affect stigma directly.
